# Figma Bridge — Cline Custom Instructions

## Tool Access

You have access to Figma via a local CLI bridge. All commands go through:
```
node /path/to/figma-mcp-bridge/figma-cli.js <command> [args]
```

Set `FIGMA_API=http://localhost:3000` if the server runs on a different port.

## Available Commands

### Read (GET)
| Command | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| `status` | Check if Figma plugin is connected |
| `selection` | Get currently selected layers (compact JSON) |
| `styles` | Get local paint/text/effect styles |
| `components` | Get local components list |
| `node <id>` | Get node details by ID |

### Write (POST)
| Command | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| `create <TYPE> [flags]` | Create a node (FRAME, RECTANGLE, TEXT, ELLIPSE, etc.) |
| `modify <id> [flags]` | Modify an existing node |
| `delete <id> [<id>...]` | Delete one or more nodes |
| `export <id> [--format png/svg]` | Export node as image |

### Universal
| Command | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| `run <file.js>` | Execute Figma Plugin API code from a JS file |
| `eval <code>` | Execute a short inline expression |
| `batch <file.json>` | Execute multiple operations from a JSON file |

## Preferred Workflow

### For complex operations, ALWAYS use `run <file.js>`:
1. Write a `.js` file with Figma Plugin API code
2. Execute it with `node figma-cli.js run <file.js>`
3. Check the returned result

This avoids JSON escaping issues that occur with curl/inline JSON.

### For simple reads, use direct commands:
```
node figma-cli.js selection
node figma-cli.js node 1:23
```

### For repetitive bulk operations, use `batch <file.json>`:
Write a JSON array of operations:
```json
[
  {"type": "CREATE_NODE", "payload": {"nodeType": "FRAME", "properties": {"name": "Card", "width": 320, "height": 200}}},
  {"type": "MODIFY_NODE", "payload": {"nodeId": "1:23", "properties": {"fills": [{"type": "SOLID", "color": {"r": 0.1, "g": 0.1, "b": 0.2}}]}}}
]
```

## Design Rules

ALWAYS follow the design system defined in `design-system.md` when creating or modifying designs.
Before starting any design task:
1. Read `design-system.md` for tokens and conventions
2. Read the current selection or target frame to understand context
3. Use design tokens (colors, spacing, typography) from the system

## Code Execution Tips

When writing `.js` files for `run`:
- The `figma` global object is available
- Use `async/await` (the code runs in an async context)
- Return a value with `return` to get results
- Always `await figma.loadFontAsync(...)` before setting text
- Use `figma.getNodeByIdAsync(id)` (not `getNodeById`)
- For bulk node creation, process in chunks to avoid UI freezes

### Critical API Rules

1. **`layoutSizingHorizontal = "FILL"`** must be set AFTER appending the node to an auto-layout parent:
   ```js
   parent.appendChild(child);
   child.layoutSizingHorizontal = "FILL";  // Must come after appendChild
   ```

2. **`effects` (DROP_SHADOW)** requires `blendMode`, `spread`, `visible` fields:
   ```js
   node.effects = [{type: "DROP_SHADOW", color: {r:0,g:0,b:0,a:0.1}, offset: {x:0,y:4}, radius: 6, spread: 0, visible: true, blendMode: "NORMAL"}];
   ```

3. **Font loading** must happen before any text manipulation:
   ```js
   await figma.loadFontAsync({family: "Inter", style: "Regular"});
   ```

4. **Node lookup** must use async version:
   ```js
   const node = await figma.getNodeByIdAsync("1:23");  // NOT figma.getNodeById()
   ```

### Common Patterns

**Create a card with auto-layout:**
```js
const card = figma.createFrame();
card.name = "Card";
card.resize(320, 0);
card.layoutMode = "VERTICAL";
card.primaryAxisSizingMode = "AUTO";
card.counterAxisSizingMode = "FIXED";
card.paddingLeft = card.paddingRight = card.paddingTop = card.paddingBottom = 16;
card.itemSpacing = 8;
card.cornerRadius = 8;
card.fills = [{type: "SOLID", color: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1}}];
return card.id;
```

**Add text to a parent:**
```js
await figma.loadFontAsync({family: "Inter", style: "Regular"});
const text = figma.createText();
text.characters = "Hello World";
text.fontSize = 16;
text.fills = [{type: "SOLID", color: {r: 0.1, g: 0.1, b: 0.1}}];
const parent = await figma.getNodeByIdAsync("PARENT_ID");
if (parent && "appendChild" in parent) parent.appendChild(text);
return text.id;
```

**Read all text nodes on current page:**
```js
const texts = figma.currentPage.findAll(n => n.type === "TEXT");
return texts.map(t => ({id: t.id, name: t.name, text: t.characters}));
```

## Response Format

All responses are compact JSON by default:
- Colors are HEX strings (`"#1a1a2e"`)
- Default values (visible: true, opacity: 1) are omitted
- Layout padding is `[top, right, bottom, left]` array
- Font is `"Family/Style"` string (e.g., `"Inter/Bold"`)

Use `--verbose true` flag for full Figma data (includes CSS, all properties).
Use `--depth N` to limit tree traversal depth.

## Error Handling

- If you get "Figma plugin not connected", ask the user to open Figma and run the plugin
- If you get a timeout error, the operation might be too complex — break it into smaller steps
- Check `node figma-cli.js status` before starting work

## Context Management

Your context window is limited. Follow these rules:
1. Use `--depth 0` or `--depth 1` for initial exploration of deep hierarchies
2. Drill into specific nodes with `node <id>` only when needed
3. Avoid reading the full selection when you only need specific properties
4. For design tasks, work section-by-section rather than building everything at once
5. After creating complex layouts, verify with `node <id> --depth 1` rather than reading entire tree
